 *Cc:* Hirsch, Fred <fred.hirsch@MSSM.EDU>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

Dear Dr. García-Sastre, 

 

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publication below. As a next step we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication.  

Please send the requested data by COB *9.29.21.*  

 

 
|Award |PMID |Title |Journal |
|CA260560|33547084|Nsp1 protein of SARS-CoV-2 disrupts the mRNA export machinery to inhibit host gene expression.|Science advances|

 

The Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you as we prepare the data set(s) for submission to a public (open access) data repository on your behalf.   

NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission: 

 
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.   
 * The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above. 
 * When you accept the invitation, you will be asked to create an account to access the data submission folder on NIH Box.  
 * If you have any issues creating your account email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov] 
 * Once the account is created you will be able to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication. 
 * Please upload the data files to the *submitted_data*
 * If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.   

 

Our curators will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have as they prepare the data for submission to a public data repository.   If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still sign up for the NIH Box account because we will still need your assistance documenting that information and will be using NIH Box for this as well.  

 

As you prepare your submission be sure to: 
 * Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include dates or other PHI) 
 * Include a brief description of the column names 
 * Include any applicable units 
 * Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes,  1= no)   
 * Define any blank values (e.g. not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.) 

 

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].  

 

Thank you so much!

 

Best,

Alexander Liu

 

 

 

Alexander Liu (Contractor)

SeroNet Curator

 

Essential Software Inc. (ESI)

Center for Biomedical Informatics and Information Technology (CBIIT)

9609 Medical Center Drive,

Rockville, MD 20850

column342:
Friday, 17 Dec 2021 11:41 AM;liualg;Hello Adolfo,

 

We have compiled a list of the different types of data we are looking for. We have broken this down by paper (PMID). Please let us you if you have any questions.

 

*PMID33115920:*
 * Figure 1 data:  Data that was used to create the figures 1A and 1B. The 1B data has date in it but it is a census count (numbers positive on that day) of that day so should be fine. However, no particular data should be provided related to patient information (HIPAA rules).

 
 * Figure 2: This data could be separate or same from the excel file used in the Figure 1. It has correlations between ELISA and Neutralization (2A) and percentage count. 

 
 * Figure 3: ELISA and microneutralization data used for this figure, which used a subset of 121 volunteers (A-F) and data from subset of 36 individuals used to construct figure G and Figure H.

 
 * For all these data, we would like to see demographics data for the subjects for our future use.

 

*PMID33142304:*
 * Data that is used to create Figure 1, 2 and 3, they are about seroprevalence, antibody titers against full length spike proteins and the number of confirmed cases in NYC (Figure 1), subclasses (Figure 2) and urgent care group only (Figure 3). 

 
 * The paper states that the data were retrieved from : [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]. This is a board which gets updated constantly in my guess. But we need exact data which they used to create those tables/figures when they conducted that study. 

 

*PMID33961839:*
 * Relevant data would be qPCR findings in different types of tissue types studied (from 73 organs from deceased COVID-19 patients) and their comparison chart which was used for final evaluation/analysis. qPCR data (cycle threshold 24 and 34), suggesting low viral loads in lungs is also useful for our purpose.

 
 * If only one patient had detectable levels of viral load (as written in the paper), the findings of that patient would be data requested. If tissues assays did not detect any virus in other 59 organ sections, it should be labelled ‘not detected’ in the submitted excel file. 

 
 * Complete demographic information of the patients included in the paper (including race, ethnicity) would be helpful if it is available to share, although some is already available in the paper, table 1).

 

*PMID33142304*
 * Looking at the provided data and comparing with all the figures, could you please confirm that all the figures are derived from the supplementary data provided. If this is the case, it would be acceptable.
 * There are source data files associated with this paper.
 * Links are : [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM2_ESM.xlsx] and [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM3_ESM.xlsx]
 * The paper also provides retrieval source url: [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]

 

*PMID34145263*
 * The data provided with the paper looks good. Please supply metadata to explain some of the values (what do blanks mean – missing values, what abbreviations mean)

 

*PMID33440148*
 * Please send data for:

 * Figure 1 f and g: qRT-PCR for intracellular viral RNA measurements data for the figures created

 
 * Figure 2: qRT-PCR data to create the graphs and bar diagrams.

 
 * Figure 3: qRT-PCR data for the bar diagrams/figures. Immunofluorescence images not required.

 
 * Figure 4: quantitative RT-PCR data for figure 4b. And data for A, B, C, E, F.

 
 * Figure 5: 5A: qRT-PCR data, 5b: qRT-PCR data, 5c: data from 3 independent experiments with technical replicates (as stated in the legends).

 
 * Basically, could we please have the data which has been used for these diagrams/figures/bar diagrams. Note: We will not ask for copies of Images, and can be skipped.

 

I know this is a lot, but if you could get back to us by *10/22/21*, that would be much appreciated!

 

Thank you,

Alex

Dear Mrigendra,

I had a question about the SeroNet policy on the uploading of the data. I know we have talked about the policy multiple times in SeroNet meetings, I am in no way trying to cause a problem.

 

In this case we provided one figure of data for the manuscript. The rest of the data was completed by other groups and funded outside of SeroNet.

My thought was to upload the data that we completed in our laboratory. I have seen all of the analyzed data but not all of the raw data, nor do I have or own the raw data from other institutions.

 

How does that fit with the policy?

 

Best

James
column342:
Tuesday, 14 Dec 2021 05:32 PM;bastolamm;On Dec 13, 2021, 5:08 PM -0600, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <[elaine.freund@nih.gov|mailto:elaine.freund@nih.gov]>, wrote:

Hi James,

I am the Manager of the Data Coordinating Center and have been working closely with the Data Ops group on the Data Sharing Policy.  

We do require the data that support the publication. This includes “final” research data generated by collaborators, so there is no need track down raw data. I can reassure you that publications with no human subjects are easier to deal with and won’t be huge burden on whomever is going to work with us on data. We will fill out the study ImmPort templates and ask the data point of contact to do review prior to release.  You have noted you don’t own the data. Since this is regarding a vaccine, are there proprietary concerns?

Best Regards,

Elaine

 To: Adolfo García-Sastre <adolfo.garcia-sastre@mssm.edu>, SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C] <mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov>
 Cc: Hirsch, Fred <fred.hirsch@MSSM.EDU>
 Subject: Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

Dear Dr. García-Sastre,

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publication below. As a next step we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication.

Please send the requested data by COB 9.29.21.

Award PMID Title Journal 
 CA260560 33115920 Robust neutralizing antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 infection persist for months. Science (New York, N.Y.)

The Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you as we prepare the data set(s) for submission to a public (open access) data repository on your behalf.

NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission:

You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box. 
 The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above. 
 When you accept the invitation, you will be asked to create an account to access the data submission folder on NIH Box. 
 If you have any issues creating your account email: CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov 
 Once the account is created you will be able to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication. 
 Please upload the data files to the submitted_data
 If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.

Our curators will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have as they prepare the data for submission to a public data repository. If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still sign up for the NIH Box account because we will still need your assistance documenting that information and will be using NIH Box for this as well.

As you prepare your submission be sure to:

Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include dates or other PHI) 
 Include a brief description of the column names 
 Include any applicable units 
 Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes, 1= no) 
 Define any blank values (e.g. not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.)

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov.

Thank you so much!

Best,

Alexander Liu

Alexander Liu (Contractor)

SeroNet Curator

Center for Biomedical Informatics and Information Technology (CBIIT)

9609 Medical Center Drive,

Rockville, MD 20850

*From:* Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C] <alexander.liu@nih.gov>
 *Date:* Wednesday, October 13, 2021 at 9:37 AM
 *To:* Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C] <debra.hope@nih.gov>, Adolfo García-Sastre <adolfo.garcia-sastre@mssm.edu>, Miorin, Lisa <lisa.miorin@mssm.edu>, Ryan Camping <ryan.camping@mssm.edu>, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <elaine.freund@nih.gov>
 *Cc:* Teresa Aydillo Gomez <teresa.aydillo-gomez@mssm.edu>, SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C] <mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet data sets-request for data point of contact

Hello Adolfo,

 

We have compiled a list of the different types of data we are looking for. We have broken this down by paper (PMID). Please let us you if you have any questions.

 

*PMID33115920:*
 * Figure 1 data:  Data that was used to create the figures 1A and 1B. The 1B data has date in it but it is a census count (numbers positive on that day) of that day so should be fine. However, no particular data should be provided related to patient information (HIPAA rules).

 
 * Figure 2: This data could be separate or same from the excel file used in the Figure 1. It has correlations between ELISA and Neutralization (2A) and percentage count. 

 
 * Figure 3: ELISA and microneutralization data used for this figure, which used a subset of 121 volunteers (A-F) and data from subset of 36 individuals used to construct figure G and Figure H.

 
 * For all these data, we would like to see demographics data for the subjects for our future use.

 

*PMID33142304:*
 * Data that is used to create Figure 1, 2 and 3, they are about seroprevalence, antibody titers against full length spike proteins and the number of confirmed cases in NYC (Figure 1), subclasses (Figure 2) and urgent care group only (Figure 3). 

 
 * The paper states that the data were retrieved from : [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]. This is a board which gets updated constantly in my guess. But we need exact data which they used to create those tables/figures when they conducted that study. 

 

*PMID33961839:*
 * Relevant data would be qPCR findings in different types of tissue types studied (from 73 organs from deceased COVID-19 patients) and their comparison chart which was used for final evaluation/analysis. qPCR data (cycle threshold 24 and 34), suggesting low viral loads in lungs is also useful for our purpose.

 
 * If only one patient had detectable levels of viral load (as written in the paper), the findings of that patient would be data requested. If tissues assays did not detect any virus in other 59 organ sections, it should be labelled ‘not detected’ in the submitted excel file. 

 
 * Complete demographic information of the patients included in the paper (including race, ethnicity) would be helpful if it is available to share, although some is already available in the paper, table 1).

 

*PMID33142304*
 * Looking at the provided data and comparing with all the figures, could you please confirm that all the figures are derived from the supplementary data provided. If this is the case, it would be acceptable.
 * There are source data files associated with this paper.
 * Links are : [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM2_ESM.xlsx] and [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM3_ESM.xlsx]
 * The paper also provides retrieval source url: [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]

 

*PMID34145263*
 * The data provided with the paper looks good. Please supply metadata to explain some of the values (what do blanks mean – missing values, what abbreviations mean)

 

*PMID33440148*
 * Please send data for:

 * Figure 1 f and g: qRT-PCR for intracellular viral RNA measurements data for the figures created

 
 * Figure 2: qRT-PCR data to create the graphs and bar diagrams.

 
 * Figure 3: qRT-PCR data for the bar diagrams/figures. Immunofluorescence images not required.

 
 * Figure 4: quantitative RT-PCR data for figure 4b. And data for A, B, C, E, F.

 
 * Figure 5: 5A: qRT-PCR data, 5b: qRT-PCR data, 5c: data from 3 independent experiments with technical replicates (as stated in the legends).

 
 * Basically, could we please have the data which has been used for these diagrams/figures/bar diagrams. Note: We will not ask for copies of Images, and can be skipped.

 

I know this is a lot, but if you could get back to us by *10/22/21*, that would be much appreciated!

 

Thank you,

Alex

 *Cc:* Hirsch, Fred <fred.hirsch@MSSM.EDU>
 *Subject:* Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

Dear Dr. García-Sastre, 

 

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publication below. As a next step we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication.  

Please send the requested data by COB *9.29.21.*  

 

 
|Award |PMID |Title |Journal |
|CA260560|33142304|Repeated cross-sectional sero-monitoring of SARS-CoV-2 in New York City.|Nature|

 

The Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you as we prepare the data set(s) for submission to a public (open access) data repository on your behalf.   

NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission: 

 
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.   
 * The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above. 
 * When you accept the invitation, you will be asked to create an account to access the data submission folder on NIH Box.  
 * If you have any issues creating your account email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov] 
 * Once the account is created you will be able to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication. 
 * Please upload the data files to the *submitted_data*
 * If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.   

 

Our curators will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have as they prepare the data for submission to a public data repository.   If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still sign up for the NIH Box account because we will still need your assistance documenting that information and will be using NIH Box for this as well.  

 

As you prepare your submission be sure to: 
 * Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include dates or other PHI) 
 * Include a brief description of the column names 
 * Include any applicable units 
 * Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes,  1= no)   
 * Define any blank values (e.g. not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.) 

 

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].  

 

Thank you so much!

 

Best,

Alexander Liu

Tuesday, 14 Dec 2021 01:42 PM;liualg;*From:* Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C] <alexander.liu@nih.gov>
 *Date:* Wednesday, October 13, 2021 at 9:37 AM
 *To:* Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C] <debra.hope@nih.gov>, Adolfo García-Sastre <adolfo.garcia-sastre@mssm.edu>, Miorin, Lisa <lisa.miorin@mssm.edu>, Ryan Camping <ryan.camping@mssm.edu>, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <elaine.freund@nih.gov>
 *Cc:* Teresa Aydillo Gomez <teresa.aydillo-gomez@mssm.edu>, SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C] <mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet data sets-request for data point of contact

Hello Adolfo,

 

We have compiled a list of the different types of data we are looking for. We have broken this down by paper (PMID). Please let us you if you have any questions.

 

*PMID33115920:*
 * Figure 1 data:  Data that was used to create the figures 1A and 1B. The 1B data has date in it but it is a census count (numbers positive on that day) of that day so should be fine. However, no particular data should be provided related to patient information (HIPAA rules).

 
 * Figure 2: This data could be separate or same from the excel file used in the Figure 1. It has correlations between ELISA and Neutralization (2A) and percentage count. 

 
 * Figure 3: ELISA and microneutralization data used for this figure, which used a subset of 121 volunteers (A-F) and data from subset of 36 individuals used to construct figure G and Figure H.

 
 * For all these data, we would like to see demographics data for the subjects for our future use.

 

*PMID33142304:*
 * Data that is used to create Figure 1, 2 and 3, they are about seroprevalence, antibody titers against full length spike proteins and the number of confirmed cases in NYC (Figure 1), subclasses (Figure 2) and urgent care group only (Figure 3). 

 
 * The paper states that the data were retrieved from : [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]. This is a board which gets updated constantly in my guess. But we need exact data which they used to create those tables/figures when they conducted that study. 

 

*PMID33961839:*
 * Relevant data would be qPCR findings in different types of tissue types studied (from 73 organs from deceased COVID-19 patients) and their comparison chart which was used for final evaluation/analysis. qPCR data (cycle threshold 24 and 34), suggesting low viral loads in lungs is also useful for our purpose.

 
 * If only one patient had detectable levels of viral load (as written in the paper), the findings of that patient would be data requested. If tissues assays did not detect any virus in other 59 organ sections, it should be labelled ‘not detected’ in the submitted excel file. 

 
 * Complete demographic information of the patients included in the paper (including race, ethnicity) would be helpful if it is available to share, although some is already available in the paper, table 1).

 

*PMID33142304*
 * Looking at the provided data and comparing with all the figures, could you please confirm that all the figures are derived from the supplementary data provided. If this is the case, it would be acceptable.
 * There are source data files associated with this paper.
 * Links are : [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM2_ESM.xlsx] and [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM3_ESM.xlsx]
 * The paper also provides retrieval source url: [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]

 

*PMID34145263*
 * The data provided with the paper looks good. Please supply metadata to explain some of the values (what do blanks mean – missing values, what abbreviations mean)

 

*PMID33440148*
 * Please send data for:

 * Figure 1 f and g: qRT-PCR for intracellular viral RNA measurements data for the figures created

 
 * Figure 2: qRT-PCR data to create the graphs and bar diagrams.

 
 * Figure 3: qRT-PCR data for the bar diagrams/figures. Immunofluorescence images not required.

 
 * Figure 4: quantitative RT-PCR data for figure 4b. And data for A, B, C, E, F.

 
 * Figure 5: 5A: qRT-PCR data, 5b: qRT-PCR data, 5c: data from 3 independent experiments with technical replicates (as stated in the legends).

 
 * Basically, could we please have the data which has been used for these diagrams/figures/bar diagrams. Note: We will not ask for copies of Images, and can be skipped.

 

I know this is a lot, but if you could get back to us by *10/22/21*, that would be much appreciated!

 

Thank you,

Alex

 *Cc:* Hirsch, Fred <fred.hirsch@MSSM.EDU>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

Dear Dr. García-Sastre, 

 

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publication below. As a next step we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication.  

Please send the requested data by COB *9.29.21.*  

 

 
|Award |PMID |Title |Journal |
|CA260560|33440148|MDA5 Governs the Innate Immune Response to SARS-CoV-2 in Lung Epithelial Cells.|Cell reports|

 

The Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you as we prepare the data set(s) for submission to a public (open access) data repository on your behalf.   

NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission: 

 
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.   
 * The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above. 
 * When you accept the invitation, you will be asked to create an account to access the data submission folder on NIH Box.  
 * If you have any issues creating your account email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov] 
 * Once the account is created you will be able to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication. 
 * Please upload the data files to the *submitted_data*
 * If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.   

 

Our curators will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have as they prepare the data for submission to a public data repository.   If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still sign up for the NIH Box account because we will still need your assistance documenting that information and will be using NIH Box for this as well.  

 

As you prepare your submission be sure to: 
 * Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include dates or other PHI) 
 * Include a brief description of the column names 
 * Include any applicable units 
 * Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes,  1= no)   
 * Define any blank values (e.g. not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.) 

 

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].  

 

Thank you so much!

 

Best,

Alexander Liu

 

 

 

Alexander Liu (Contractor)

SeroNet Curator

 

Essential Software Inc. (ESI)

Center for Biomedical Informatics and Information Technology (CBIIT)

9609 Medical Center Drive,

Rockville, MD 20850

Email: liualg@nih.gov

Thursday, 9 Dec 2021 11:29 AM;liualg;*From:* Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C] <alexander.liu@nih.gov>
 *Date:* Wednesday, October 13, 2021 at 9:37 AM
 *To:* Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C] <debra.hope@nih.gov>, Adolfo García-Sastre <adolfo.garcia-sastre@mssm.edu>, Miorin, Lisa <lisa.miorin@mssm.edu>, Ryan Camping <ryan.camping@mssm.edu>, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <elaine.freund@nih.gov>
 *Cc:* Teresa Aydillo Gomez <teresa.aydillo-gomez@mssm.edu>, SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C] <mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet data sets-request for data point of contact

Hello Adolfo,

 

We have compiled a list of the different types of data we are looking for. We have broken this down by paper (PMID). Please let us you if you have any questions.

 

*PMID33115920:*
 * Figure 1 data:  Data that was used to create the figures 1A and 1B. The 1B data has date in it but it is a census count (numbers positive on that day) of that day so should be fine. However, no particular data should be provided related to patient information (HIPAA rules).

 
 * Figure 2: This data could be separate or same from the excel file used in the Figure 1. It has correlations between ELISA and Neutralization (2A) and percentage count. 

 
 * Figure 3: ELISA and microneutralization data used for this figure, which used a subset of 121 volunteers (A-F) and data from subset of 36 individuals used to construct figure G and Figure H.

 
 * For all these data, we would like to see demographics data for the subjects for our future use.

 

*PMID33142304:*
 * Data that is used to create Figure 1, 2 and 3, they are about seroprevalence, antibody titers against full length spike proteins and the number of confirmed cases in NYC (Figure 1), subclasses (Figure 2) and urgent care group only (Figure 3). 

 
 * The paper states that the data were retrieved from : [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]. This is a board which gets updated constantly in my guess. But we need exact data which they used to create those tables/figures when they conducted that study. 

 

*PMID33961839:*
 * Relevant data would be qPCR findings in different types of tissue types studied (from 73 organs from deceased COVID-19 patients) and their comparison chart which was used for final evaluation/analysis. qPCR data (cycle threshold 24 and 34), suggesting low viral loads in lungs is also useful for our purpose.

 
 * If only one patient had detectable levels of viral load (as written in the paper), the findings of that patient would be data requested. If tissues assays did not detect any virus in other 59 organ sections, it should be labelled ‘not detected’ in the submitted excel file. 

 
 * Complete demographic information of the patients included in the paper (including race, ethnicity) would be helpful if it is available to share, although some is already available in the paper, table 1).

 

*PMID33142304*
 * Looking at the provided data and comparing with all the figures, could you please confirm that all the figures are derived from the supplementary data provided. If this is the case, it would be acceptable.
 * There are source data files associated with this paper.
 * Links are : [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM2_ESM.xlsx] and [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM3_ESM.xlsx]
 * The paper also provides retrieval source url: [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]

 

*PMID34145263*
 * The data provided with the paper looks good. Please supply metadata to explain some of the values (what do blanks mean – missing values, what abbreviations mean)

 

*PMID33440148*
 * Please send data for:

 * Figure 1 f and g: qRT-PCR for intracellular viral RNA measurements data for the figures created

 
 * Figure 2: qRT-PCR data to create the graphs and bar diagrams.

 
 * Figure 3: qRT-PCR data for the bar diagrams/figures. Immunofluorescence images not required.

 
 * Figure 4: quantitative RT-PCR data for figure 4b. And data for A, B, C, E, F.

 
 * Figure 5: 5A: qRT-PCR data, 5b: qRT-PCR data, 5c: data from 3 independent experiments with technical replicates (as stated in the legends).

 
 * Basically, could we please have the data which has been used for these diagrams/figures/bar diagrams. Note: We will not ask for copies of Images, and can be skipped.

 

I know this is a lot, but if you could get back to us by *10/22/21*, that would be much appreciated!

 

Thank you,

Alex

*Date:* Monday, November 15, 2021 at 9:35 AM
*To:* "Vidal,Samuel (BIDMC - Barouch Med Vaccine Research)" <svidal1@bidmc.harvard.edu>
*Subject:* Re: Some questions on your recent data submission

 

Dear Dr. Vidal,

Thank you for your submission which we found mostly complete, with no missing values or other major issues.

 

However, we had minor questions regarding the dataset, as follows.

 
 * The column C is named ‘Comorbidity number’. Comparing it with the original manuscript, the header seems same as ‘Major comorbidity(ies)’, and the comorbidity number means the count of major comorbidities indicated in the original paper. We found the numbers correlating in all rows except rows 8 and 18, where the submitted data sets has 3 but the original manuscript has two listed in each rows.

 
 * Also, the hospital duration days (Column D in submitted data) in subject 20 is listed 26 in submitted data and has a value of 32 in published table 1 (original publication), with different column header (Admission duration).

 

For better alignment with published resources and better clarity to users, our questions are :
 * Does ‘Comorbidity number’ mean number of comorbidities each subject had? For better clarity, can the column header be changed to: ‘Number of Major Comorbidity(ies)’?
 * Can you reconfirm the numbers in forementioned rows in the submitted dataset?

 

Please let us know if you have issues accessing NIH Box or if you have any other difficulties.

 

Thank you so much,

Mrigendra Mani Bastola (Contractor)

NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission:
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to +[SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov]+.

Thursday, 9 Dec 2021 11:46 AM;liualg;*From:* Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C] <alexander.liu@nih.gov>
 *Date:* Wednesday, October 13, 2021 at 9:37 AM
 *To:* Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C] <debra.hope@nih.gov>, Adolfo García-Sastre <adolfo.garcia-sastre@mssm.edu>, Miorin, Lisa <lisa.miorin@mssm.edu>, Ryan Camping <ryan.camping@mssm.edu>, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <elaine.freund@nih.gov>
 *Cc:* Teresa Aydillo Gomez <teresa.aydillo-gomez@mssm.edu>, SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C] <mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet data sets-request for data point of contact

Hello Adolfo,

 

We have compiled a list of the different types of data we are looking for. We have broken this down by paper (PMID). Please let us you if you have any questions.

 

*PMID33115920:*
 * Figure 1 data:  Data that was used to create the figures 1A and 1B. The 1B data has date in it but it is a census count (numbers positive on that day) of that day so should be fine. However, no particular data should be provided related to patient information (HIPAA rules).

 
 * Figure 2: This data could be separate or same from the excel file used in the Figure 1. It has correlations between ELISA and Neutralization (2A) and percentage count. 

 
 * Figure 3: ELISA and microneutralization data used for this figure, which used a subset of 121 volunteers (A-F) and data from subset of 36 individuals used to construct figure G and Figure H.

 
 * For all these data, we would like to see demographics data for the subjects for our future use.

 

*PMID33142304:*
 * Data that is used to create Figure 1, 2 and 3, they are about seroprevalence, antibody titers against full length spike proteins and the number of confirmed cases in NYC (Figure 1), subclasses (Figure 2) and urgent care group only (Figure 3). 

 
 * The paper states that the data were retrieved from : [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]. This is a board which gets updated constantly in my guess. But we need exact data which they used to create those tables/figures when they conducted that study. 

 

*PMID33961839:*
 * Relevant data would be qPCR findings in different types of tissue types studied (from 73 organs from deceased COVID-19 patients) and their comparison chart which was used for final evaluation/analysis. qPCR data (cycle threshold 24 and 34), suggesting low viral loads in lungs is also useful for our purpose.

 
 * If only one patient had detectable levels of viral load (as written in the paper), the findings of that patient would be data requested. If tissues assays did not detect any virus in other 59 organ sections, it should be labelled ‘not detected’ in the submitted excel file. 

 
 * Complete demographic information of the patients included in the paper (including race, ethnicity) would be helpful if it is available to share, although some is already available in the paper, table 1).

 

*PMID33142304*
 * Looking at the provided data and comparing with all the figures, could you please confirm that all the figures are derived from the supplementary data provided. If this is the case, it would be acceptable.
 * There are source data files associated with this paper.
 * Links are : [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM2_ESM.xlsx] and [https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41586-020-2912-6/MediaObjects/41586_2020_2912_MOESM3_ESM.xlsx]
 * The paper also provides retrieval source url: [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page]

 

*PMID34145263*
 * The data provided with the paper looks good. Please supply metadata to explain some of the values (what do blanks mean – missing values, what abbreviations mean)

 

*PMID33440148*
 * Please send data for:

 * Figure 1 f and g: qRT-PCR for intracellular viral RNA measurements data for the figures created

 
 * Figure 2: qRT-PCR data to create the graphs and bar diagrams.

 
 * Figure 3: qRT-PCR data for the bar diagrams/figures. Immunofluorescence images not required.

 
 * Figure 4: quantitative RT-PCR data for figure 4b. And data for A, B, C, E, F.

 
 * Figure 5: 5A: qRT-PCR data, 5b: qRT-PCR data, 5c: data from 3 independent experiments with technical replicates (as stated in the legends).

 
 * Basically, could we please have the data which has been used for these diagrams/figures/bar diagrams. Note: We will not ask for copies of Images, and can be skipped.

 

I know this is a lot, but if you could get back to us by *10/22/21*, that would be much appreciated!

 

Thank you,

Alex

Dear Dr. Sanchez-Lopez,

 

Thank you for your submission. We intend to upload the submitted files in the data files as study data files. For better user accessibility, we need files in spreadsheet format with no missing values or abbreviations.

 

Upon reviewing the submitted data, we noted following missing information. Would you please kindly submit the missing information as listed below?

 

Please provide spreadsheet format (e.g. excel, csv) for following files:

Dear Dr. Mina, 

 

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publication below. As a next step we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication.  

Please provide the requested data by COB 12/08/2021.

 

 
|*Award*|*PMID*|*Title*|*Journal*|
|CA261277|34083451|Estimating epidemiologic dynamics from cross-sectional viral load distributions.|Science (New York, N.Y.)|

 

The Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you as we prepare the data set(s) for submission to a public (open access) data repository on your behalf.    

NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission:  

  
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.    

o        The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above.  
 * When you accept the invitation, you will be asked to create an account to access the data submission folder on NIH Box.   

o         If you have any issues creating your account email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov]  
 * Once the account is created you will be able to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication.  

o        Please upload the data files to the *submitted_data* folder.  
 *  If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.    

  

Our curators will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have as they prepare the data for submission to a public data repository.   If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still sign up for the NIH Box account because we will still need your assistance documenting that information and will be using NIH Box for this as well.   

 

As you prepare your submission be sure to: 
 * Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include dates except year, geographic subdivisions smaller than state, or other PHI) 
 * Include a brief description of the column names 
 * Include any applicable units 
 * Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes, 1= no)   
 * Define any blank values (e.g., not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.) 

 

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].  

 

 

  

Thank you so much, 

 

Mrigendra Mani Bastola (Contractor)

Monday, 13 Dec 2021 09:40 AM;bastolamm;*From:* "Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C]" <[elaine.freund@nih.gov|mailto:elaine.freund@nih.gov]>
*Date:* Friday, December 10, 2021 at 4:21 PM

*Cc:* "Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C]" <[mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov|mailto:mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov]>, "Hope, Debra (NIH/NCI) [C]" <[debra.hope@nih.gov|mailto:debra.hope@nih.gov]>, "Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C]" <[alexander.liu@nih.gov|mailto:alexander.liu@nih.gov]>
*Subject:* RE: Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

 

Hello James,

I am the Manager of the Data Coordinating Center and I sincerely apologize for the delay in responding to your e-mail about dates in your data. I asked Mani to let me respond and I dropped the ball.

 

Unfortunately SeroNet cannot accept any data that contains any Safe Harbor PHI elements which includes dates that are more granular than year. In addition ImmPort will not accept data from SeroNet that contains PHI. Your paper is great and I can see why the journal went ahead and published dates. Normally I would ask for time intervals or numbered time points, but meaning is lost.

 

I am going to escalate this matter to NCI. Before I do, I would like to gather more data. Would you be able to schedule a call with me next week so I can understand a bit more about your process and conversations with the journal. For example, I’d ask did you get expert determination of de-identification for release of dates to the public? Or is use of dates covered by an informed consent? If so, please suggest a few time slots and I will send an invite.

 

Best Regards,

Elaine

Best wishes,

James

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].

The Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you as we prepare the data set(s) for submission to a public (open access) data repository on your behalf.    

NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission:  

  
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.   
 * The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above. 
 * When you accept the invitation, you will be asked to create an account to access the data submission folder on NIH Box.  
 *  If you have any issues creating your account email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov] 
 * Once the account is created you will be able to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication. 
 * Please upload the data files to the *submitted_data* 
 *  If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.   

  

Our curators will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have as they prepare the data for submission to a public data repository.   If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still sign up for the NIH Box account because we will still need your assistance documenting that information and will be using NIH Box for this as well.

 * Define any blank values (e.g., not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.)
